---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro'
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro'
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro'
---
<Base title="About" description="Ravenburst is built by one person, for writers who take their craft seriously.">
  <Nav />
  <main class="pt-32 pb-20 px-6 max-w-2xl mx-auto">
    <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-serif font-bold mb-8">About Ravenburst</h1>

    <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-rb-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
      <p class="text-xl text-rb-text">
        Ravenburst is built by one person, for writers who take their craft seriously.
      </p>
      <p>
        I got frustrated. Every "AI writing tool" wanted to write for me.
        Every writing app wanted a monthly subscription. Every "professional" tool was designed
        for people who wanted features, not for people who wanted to write.
      </p>
      <p>
        So I built the tool I wanted. One that gets out of the way when you're writing,
        and earns its keep when you need it — catching the continuity errors you missed,
        asking the structural questions a good editor would ask, never putting a single
        word of your story on the page for you.
      </p>
      <p>
        The AI rule in Ravenburst is enforced in code, not policy. Every AI call includes a
        system prompt that explicitly forbids prose generation. It's not a toggle. It's not
        a setting you can turn off. Because your story belongs to you — not to a language model.
      </p>
      <p>
        The name is a nod to Edgar Allan Poe's The Raven, and a burst of creativity.
        The moment a story breaks through, Ravenburst is where that happens.
      </p>
      <p class="text-rb-text font-medium">— Matthew Pitts</p>
    </div>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Base>
